|compilation = yes
|MC = 92 of 100<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/ps2/finalfantasyxii| title= Final Fantasy XII | date=2006-10-31| work= Metacritic| accessdate=2007-12-07}}</ref>
}}

''Final Fantasy XII'' sold more than 1,764,000 copies in its first week in Japan, almost equaling the sales of ''[[Final Fantasy X]]'' in its first week.<ref>{{cite web | author=Jenkins, David| date=2006-03-24| title=Japanese Sales Charts, Week Ending March 19| format= | work=Media Create | url=http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=8671 | accessdate=2006-08-14}}</ref> The total number of copies sold stood at 2,150,671 after five weeks of release.<ref>{{cite web | author=| date=2006-04-20| title=Weekly software sales for 4/10 - 4/16| format= | work=Media Create | url=http://www.gamesarefun.com/news.php?newsid=6225 | accessdate=2006-08-14}}</ref> A Square-Enix conference report stated that ''Final Fantasy XII'' has sold more than 2.38 million copies in Japan as of [[May 24]], [[2006]].<ref name="2mil"/> By [[November 6]], [[2006]]—one week after its release—''Final Fantasy XII'' had shipped approximately 1.5 million copies in North America.<ref>{{cite web | author=Square Enix| date=2006-11-06| title=Square Enix Announces Record Shipment With Final Fantasy XII| format= | work=Square-Enix.com | url=http://www.square-enix.com/na/company/press/2006/1106_1/ | accessdate=2006-11-07}}</ref>  On the 7<sup>th</sup> anniversary of the Playstation 2 in the U.S. ([[October]] [[2007]]), ''Final Fantasy XII'' was listed as the tenth best selling game for the PS2.<ref>{{cite web | author=Mark Androvich | year=2007 | title=PS2 celebrates 7th anniversary | url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/content_page.php?aid=29985 | accessmonthday=October 27 | accessyear=2007}}</ref>

On [[March 16]], [[2006]], ''Final Fantasy XII''  became the sixth game to receive a 40/40 score from the Japanese gaming magazine ''[[Famitsu]]'', making it the first ''Final Fantasy'' game and the first PlayStation 2 title to do so. It is also the second Yasumi Matsuno title to garner a perfect score, the first being ''[[Vagrant Story]]''. The game was praised for its graphics, scenarios, game system, and the freshness it brought to the ''Final Fantasy'' series.<ref name="famitsu">{{cite web | author=Lumb, Jonathan| date=2006-03-08| title=FF XII Scores Perfect In Famitsu| format= | work=1up.com | url=http://1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3148658 | accessdate=2006-08-13}}</ref> The game was critically acclaimed by many reviewers outside of Japan even before its release in those territories. It was praised for its seamless transitions between FMV segments and the in-game engine,<ref name="eurogamer">{{cite web | author=Albiges, Luke | date=2006-04-18| title=Final Fantasy XII review| format= | work=Eurogamer| url=http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=63936 | accessdate=2006-08-14}}</ref> and was voted number one for Best Art Style on [[IGN]]'s weekly Top Ten.<ref>{{cite web | author=IGN Staff| date=2006-07-18| title=Top 10 Tuesday: Best Art in Videogames| format= | work=IGN.com| url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/719/719602p1.html | accessdate=2006-08-14}}</ref> ''[[Newtype (magazine)|Newtype USA]]'' named ''Final Fantasy XII'' its "Game of the Month" for November 2006, praised the gameplay, graphics, and story, and called it "the best RPG to have been released for any Sony platform."<ref>{{cite web | author=Patrick Joynt| date=2006-11-01| title=Newtype USA / Reviews / Final Fantasy XII| format= | work=Newtype-USA.com| url=http://www.newtype-usa.com/reviews/index.php?itemid=342 | accessdate=2007-01-17}}</ref>

Although GameSpot lauded the gambit and license systems as an innovative and in-depth way for the player to control the characters, it criticized them for being too complicated and difficult to adjust to, especially for newer players of the series. The reviewer also criticized the sometimes tedious back and forth travel.<ref name="Gamespotreview"/> On the other hand, GameSpot took particular note of the "excellent" voice cast.<ref name="Gamespotreview"/> IGN praised the game's rich storyline and artistic direction, shown through its "sheer depth of character". It also assuaged criticism that the gambit system would "let the game play itself", countering that gambits do not function without a player. However, it noted that, while "still extremely strong", ''Final Fantasy XII'' has one of the series' weaker soundtracks.<ref name="IGNreview"/>

Executive producer [[Akitoshi Kawazu]] was pleased by Famitsu's rating but admitted that the game was not perfect; he felt that the storyline did not meet fans' expectations.<ref>{{cite web | author= Wales, Matt | date =2006-10-26 | title=Square Talks Firsts for Final Fantasy XII | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/742/742013p1.html | work=IGN.com | accessdate=2007-06-28}}</ref> Kawazu expressed his frustration and regrets regarding the flaws in the storyline, citing creative differences between the [[PlayOnline]] and ''Final Fantasy Tactics'' members of the development team.<ref>{{cite web | author=Verlet, Nicolas | date=2006-10-24 | title=Interview : Akitoshi Kawazu (FF XII) | url=http://www.gamekult.com/articles/A0000052257/ | work=Gamekult.com | accessdate=2007-07-17 | language=French}}</ref>

''Final Fantasy XII'' was recognized by the website [[GameSpot]] as the "Best Playstation 2 Game" in their Best Games and Worst Games of 2006, as well as nominated in the "[[Game of the Year]]" and "Best Role-Playing Game" categories.<ref name="gamespot">{{cite web | author=GameSpot site staff | year=2006 | title=GameSpot's Best Games and Worst Games of 2006 | url=http://www.gamespot.com/special_features/bestof2006/platform/index.html?page=6 | work=[http://www.gamespot.com/ GameSpot] | accessdate=2007-03-09}}</ref> It also achieved "PS2 Game of the Year" and "PS2 RPG of the Year" in [[GameSpy]]'s Game of the Year 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goty.gamespy.com/2006/ps2/index14.html|title=GameSpy's Game of the Year 2006|publisher=IGN Entertainment|accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref> and won "Best PS2 RPG" and "PS2 Game of the Year" in the [[IGN]] Awards.<ref name="ignawards">{{cite web | author=IGN site staff | year=2006 | title=IGN.com presents the Best of 2006 | url=http://bestof.ign.com/2006/ps2/14.html | work=[http://www.ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=2007-03-09}}</ref><ref name="ignawards1">{{cite web | author=IGN site staff | year=2006 | title=IGN.com presents the Best of 2006 | url=http://bestof.ign.com/2006/ps2/39.html | work=[http://www.ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=2007-03-09}}</ref> ''Final Fantasy XII'' was named the "Best Game" in the 2006 ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' Awards,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edge-online.co.uk/archives/2006/12/final_fantasy_x.php|title=Final Fantasy XII is Edge's game of the year|date=2006-12-19|publisher=Edge|accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref> and it was also nominated for "Role-Playing Game of the Year" in the 10th Annual Interactive Achievement Awards by the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]].<ref name="aoiaas">{{cite web | author=AOIAAS site staff | year=2006 | title=The 10th Annual Academy of Interactive Arts and Sciences Awards | url=http://www.interactive.org/awards.php?winners&year=2007&cat=200722#200722 | work=[http://www.interactive.org/ Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences] | accessdate=2007-03-09}}</ref>

==Versions and merchandise==
[[Image:FFXIIPotionPremium.jpg|thumb|right|120px|The ''Final Fantasy XII'' "Potion" Premium Box.]]
On [[March 16]], [[2006]], [[Sony Computer Entertainment|Sony Computer Entertainment Japan]] released a special ''Final Fantasy XII'' package, which contained a ''[[PlayStation 2]]'' game system, the ''Final Fantasy XII'' game, a standard [[DualShock]] controller, and a vertical console stand.<ref>{{cite web | author=Gantayat, Anoop| date=2006-01-06| title=Final Fantasy XII PS2 Coming| format= | work=IGN.com | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/679/679404p1.html | accessdate=2006-09-01}}</ref> The Japanese third-party manufacturer Hori also released ''Final Fantasy XII'' [[memory card]]s on the day of the game's release; stickers of ''Final Fantasy XII'' characters are included.<ref>{{cite web | author=Winkler, Chris| date=2006-02-17| title=FFXII Memory Card Announced| format= | work=rpgfan.com | url=http://www.rpgfan.com/news/2006/1095.html | accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref> Game peripheral maker [[Logitech#Brand names|Logicool]] ([[Logitech]]'s Japanese branch) released a special edition ''Final Fantasy XII'' controller alongside the title on [[March 16]].<ref>{{cite web | author=Winkler, Chris| date=2006-01-15| title=FFXII PS2 Controller Announced in Japan| format= | work=rpgfan.com | url=http://www.rpgfan.com/news/2006/1025.html | accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref> [[Suntory]] produced "Final Fantasy XII [[Final Fantasy items|Potion]]"—a drink containing such ingredients as [[royal jelly]], chamomile, sage, thyme, and marjoram. The drinks became commercially available in Japan on [[March 7]], [[2006]]. Suntory also released a ''Final Fantasy XII'' Premium Box, which came with a ''Final Fantasy XII'' collector's card. The Potion was a limited edition product and is no longer available.<ref>{{cite web | author=Gantayat, Anoop| date=2006-01-19| title=Final Fantasy XII Drink Dated| format= | work=IGN.com | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/682/682201p1.html | accessdate=2006-09-01}}</ref>

Studio BentStuff published three [[Ultimania]] books: ''Final Fantasy XII Battle Ultimania'' and the ''Final Fantasy XII Scenario Ultimania'' on [[June 16]], [[2006]], and ''Final Fantasy XII Ultimania Ω'' on [[November 24]], [[2006]]. The ''Battle Ultimania'' provides a description and analysis of the new [[#Battle system|battle system]] and its components, as well as developer interviews.<ref name="Bentstuff">{{cite web | author=Studio BentStuff| year=2006-04-21| title=Studio BentStuff | format= | work=bent.co.jp | url=http://www.bent.co.jp/main/news/20060421.htm | accessdate=2007-03-25}}</ref> The ''Scenario Ultimania'' describes the main scenarios in the game, profiles on the characters and areas in Ivalice, developer interviews, and details on each location.<ref name="Bentstuff"/> Another guide, the ''Ultimania Ω'', includes [[seiyū|voice actor]] interviews, the complete story of ''Final Fantasy XII'' including additional character profiles, a collection of artworks and illustrations, the complete play guide,<ref>{{cite web | author=Studio BentStuff| date=2006-10-31| title=Studio BentStuff | format= | work=bent.co.jp | url=http://www.bent.co.jp/main/news/20061031.htm | accessdate=2007-03-25}}</ref> and a novella written by Benny Matsuyama, author of [[List of Final Fantasy media#Novles and manga|''Hoshi wo Meguru Otome'']] from the ''Final Fantasy VII Ultimania Ω Guide''.<ref>{{cite web | author=Team Animefringe| date=2005-12-01| title=The Legacy of Final Fantasy VII| format= | work=animefringe.com | url=http://www.animefringe.com/magazine/2005/12/feature/01-4.php | accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref> Another Ultimania edition, the ''Final Fantasy XII International Zodiac Job System Ultimania'', will be released on [[September 6]], [[2007]] as a guide book for the international version of the game.<ref>{{cite web | author=Studio BentStuff| year=2007-08-06| title=「ファイナルファンタジーXII インターナショナル ゾディアックジョブシステム アルティマニア」表紙公開 | format= | work=bent.co.jp | url=http://www.bent.co.jp/main/news/20070806.htm | accessdate=2007-08-18}}</ref>

For the North American release, a "Collector's Edition" was available through [[GameStop]] and [[Electronics Boutique|EB Games]].<ref>{{cite web | author=Sinclair, Brendan | year=2006-10-31 | title=Final Fantasy XII lands at retail | format= | work=GameSpot.com | url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/rpg/finalfantasy12/news.html?sid=6160785 | accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref> This edition includes the original game packaged in a metallic case along with a special bonus disc, which contains ''Final Fantasy XII'' developer interviews, an art gallery, U.S. and Japanese [[trailer (film)|trailers]], and a [[featurette]] entitled "History of ''Final Fantasy''", which gives a brief overview of most released and upcoming ''Final Fantasy'' games.<ref>{{cite web | author=Hatfield, Daemon | date=2006-10-31 | title=Final Fantasy Ships for the XIIth Time | format= | work=IGN.com | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/742/742843p1.html | accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref> On [[January 26]], [[2007]], Square Enix Product Blog revealed that the full-color Gabranth, Ashe, Balthier and Vaan [[action figure|figures]] are complete and will be available soon.<ref name="actionfigures">{{cite web | date=2007-01-26 | title=FINAL FANTASY XII PLAY ARTS | url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/se-shop/blog/200701.html | language=Japanese | work=square-enix.co.jp | accessdate=2007-03-28}}</ref>

An [[international version]] of the game called {{nihongo|''Final Fantasy XII International Zodiac Job System''|ファイナルファンタジーXII インターナショナル ゾディアックジョブシステム|Fainaru Fantajī Tuerubu Intānashonaru Zodiakku Jobu Shisutemu}}  was released in Japan on [[August 9]] [[2007]] as part of both ''Final Fantasy'' 20th anniversary and ''[[Ivalice#Ivalice Alliance|Ivalice Alliance]]''.<ref>{{cite web | author=Square Enix| date=2007| title= Square Enix Party Press Conference Announcement| format= | work= | url=http://www.square-enix.com/na/company/press/2007/0514_3/ | accessdate=2007-07-14}}</ref> The game includes twelve License Boards available (instead of the original one), each corresponding to a different Zodiac sign and [[Final Fantasy character classes|job]]. The battle system as a whole has been tweaked; guest characters and summons are controllable by the player, and pressing the L1 button accelerates the game's speed. Additionally, the game features the English voices and the [[widescreen]] 16:9 ratio support of the North American version, as well as a bonus disc based on the one initially released with the North American version. Other new features such as new licenses, new spells and new gambits have been shown as well. There is also a "[[New Game+]]" option, as well as a new "Trial Mode" which allows the player to hunt monsters in 100 different maps to gain items and money.<ref name="international">{{cite web |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q2-2007/050907a.html |title=Final Fantasy IV Remake, XII International Announced |accessdate=2007-05-09 |author=Bryan Boulette |date=2007-05-09 |work=[http://www.rpgamer.com/ RPGamer]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ffworld.com/?rub=news&page=voir&id=764 |title=FFXII International: Plus d'infos (MàJ) |accessdate=2007-05-10 |author=KujaFFman |date=2007-05-10 |work=[http://www.ffworld.com/ Final Fantasy World] |publisher= |language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ffworld.com/?rub=news&page=voir&id=771 |title=FFXII International: Des détails |accessdate=2007-05-12 |author=KujaFFman |date=2007-05-12 |work=[http://www.ffworld.com/ Final Fantasy World] |publisher= |language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author=GameSpot| date=2007| title= Final Fantasy XII International Zodiac Job System| format= | work=yahoo.com | url=http://uk.videogames.games.yahoo.com/ps2/previews/final-fantasy-xii-international--zodiac-job-system-2d2cfd.html | accessdate=2007-05-29}}</ref>

